(Continuation of #1070 (comment) as I can't reply there)

If you think it's enough to wait only for the first error from SD and subsequent requests should fail fast, then I can switch to Completable.

Thats not what I meant. Even if you switch to Completable; it doesn't have to represent the first error. It can instead represent any error since start or after the previous onNext of SD publisher. You can implement such a Completable as:
private static final class SDErrorsCompletable extends Completable {
    private static final AtomicReferenceFieldUpdater<SDErrorsCompletable, CompletableSource.Processor>
            currentProcessorUpdater = AtomicReferenceFieldUpdater.newUpdater(SDErrorsCompletable.class,
            CompletableSource.Processor.class, "currentProcessor");

    private volatile CompletableSource.Processor currentProcessor = newCompletableProcessor();

    @Override
    protected void handleSubscribe(final CompletableSource.Subscriber subscriber) {
        currentProcessor.subscribe(subscriber);
    }

    void nextSuccess() {
        CompletableSource.Processor newProcessor = newCompletableProcessor();
        CompletableSource.Processor oldProcessor = currentProcessorUpdater.getAndSet(this, newProcessor);
        oldProcessor.onComplete();
    }

    void nextError(final Throwable error) {
        CompletableSource.Processor newProcessor = newCompletableProcessor();
        CompletableSource.Processor oldProcessor = currentProcessorUpdater.getAndSet(this, newProcessor);
        oldProcessor.onError(error);
        newProcessor.onError(error);
    }
}
The positive here is that the AutoRetryStrategyProvider implementaions can be simple (directly use the passed Completable) as opposed to managing stateful Subscriber as you do now.
This is different than load balancer as the lbEventStream may potentially contain other events apart from on-ready.

